turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Good God.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Do you think it's them?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I wonder.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: And nobody knows we're here except for Freda and she wouldn't ring up.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Well it must be them then.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: What are you going to do?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: We're fine right?  Aren't we?  Whatever happens darling.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Now and always sweet.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I don't care then.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: I mean, it was, it's bound to come out sooner or later.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Hello?  Hello?  What?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: That sent shivers up my spine.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: No, wrong number.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: What are we to do if they suddenly walk in on us?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Behave exquisitely.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: With the most perfect poise?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Certainly.  And I shall probably do a court courtesy.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: um- Things that should matter dreadfully don't seem to matter at all when one's happy do they?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: What is so horrible is that one cannot stay happy.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Oh, darling.  Don't say that.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: It's true.  I mean, the whole business it's a very poor joke.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: You mean that, that sacred and beautiful thing love?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Yes.  I mean just that.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: What does that all mean?  That's what I asked myself on my quest for ultimate truth.  What does it all mean?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Don't laugh at me.  I'm serious.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: [LAUGHTER] Oh, darling.  You mustn't be serious, that's just what they want.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Who's they?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: All the futile moralists who try to make life unbearable.  Laugh at them.  Be flippant.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Laugh at all their sacred shibboleths.  Flippancy brings the acid in their damn sweetness and light.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: So if I'm to laugh at everything then I must laugh at us too.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Oh, certainly, you must.  We're figures of fun alright.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: How long will it last?  This ludicrous overbearing love of ours?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Who knows?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Shall we always want to bicker and fight?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: No.  That fire will fade along with our passion.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Well, dear, shall we want that?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Well, it depends on how well we've played.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: What happens if one of us dies?  I mean, does the other one still laugh?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Of course, yes, yes, with all his might.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: That's serious enough.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: No.  No it isn't.  That's very laughable, a cunning little mystery all done with mirrors.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Darling I believe you're talking nonsense.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Oh, and who isn't talking nonsense?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Let's be superficial and pity the poor philosophers hmmm?  Let's blow trumpets and squeakers and party as much as we can like quite idiotic school children.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Let's savor the delight of the moment.  Come kiss me darling before worms pop in and out of your eye sockets.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Elliot, worms don't pop.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I don't care what you do, you see?  As long, no I don't care what you do, see?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: You can put green paint all over your body and dance naked in the Place Vendome and rush off madly with all the men in the world and I shan't say a word as long as you love me best.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Thank you dear.  The same applies to you...

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: ...only if you ever so much as look at another woman I'll kill you.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Remember that awful scene we had in Venice?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Which particular one?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: The one when you bought a little painted wooden snake in the Piazza and put it in my bed.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Charles, that was his name, Charles.  Oh, God he was so wiggled so beautifully.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Horrible little thing.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Yeah.  I know you did.  You threw it out the window and into the Grand Canal.  I don't think I'll ever forgive you for that.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I hated it.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: How long did that rile last?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: It went on intermittently for days.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Oh, the worst one was in Cannes when you-

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: I burnt a hole in my comb too and all the towels in the bathroom.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: you're curling iron burnt a hole in my dressing gown.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: That was a rouser wasn't it?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: [LAUGHTER] Yeah.  That was the first time you ever hit me.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I didn't hit you very hard.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: The manager came in and saw us rolling on the floor, scratching and biting like panthers.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I will never forget his face. Ooh-rah [LAUGHTER].

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: How ridiculous.  How utterly, utterly ridiculous.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: We were very much younger then.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: And much sillier too.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: The real cause of that rile was Peter Burden.
